Got it — you’re asking specifically about the .class part in:

Java

Copy code
SpringApplication.run(CourseServiceApplication.class, args);
Let’s break that down clearly.

What .class means in Java
In Java, every class you write (e.g., CourseServiceApplication) has a special class literal syntax:
ClassName.class
This is not a file — it’s a way to get a Class object at runtime.
The Class object is part of Java’s reflection API and contains metadata about the class (its name, methods, annotations, etc.).
Example
Java
    Class<?> clazz = CourseServiceApplication.class;
    System.out.println(clazz.getName()); // prints "com.example.CourseServiceApplication"
Here, CourseServiceApplication.class returns a Class object representing the CourseServiceApplication type.

Why Spring Boot needs it
SpringApplication.run() has this signature:

Java
    public static ConfigurableApplicationContext run(Class<?> primarySource, String... args)

The first parameter (primarySource) tells Spring Boot:
Which class is the starting point of the application.
Where to begin component scanning (usually the package of this class and its subpackages).
Passing CourseServiceApplication.class means:
“Here’s the main application class — use it to configure and start the Spring context.”

Analogy
Think of .class as pointing to the blueprint of your class, not an object of it.
Spring Boot uses that blueprint to:

Find annotations like @SpringBootApplication
Locate beans and configurations
Start the application from that package
✅ In short:
CourseServiceApplication.class is a reference to the Class object for CourseServiceApplication, which Spring Boot uses to know where and how to start your app.